Workaround wrote:Does the radiation frequency of the star limit the habitability? I'm under the impression that red dwarves mostly put out infrared, which would limit the types of earth organisms that could use it.In most of the 'habitability' models, people are just looking for earth sized, approximately earth distance, approximately solar type stars. There are other things like atmosphere that are really important as you can imagine. Measuring atmospheres is super duper hard right now, and most of the data is pretty garbage.So yes, the type of star does limit whether the system can be habitable in practice. As does it's dynamics, etc. Too small a star and you need to be practically on top of it to stay warm, too big and you get too much radiation.
Torbjörn Larsson, OM
Ars Scholae Palatinae
Registered: Apr 8, 2011Posts: 1351
Posted: Thu Jun 27, 2013 12:08 pm
Wingsy wrote:I guess the word "habitable" applies just to microbes, since their masses range from 2.7 to 3.8 that of earth. I don't know of anyone who could inhabit a planet with 3 Gs pulling at you 24/7.No, it is habitable for complex multicellulars. In this case even humans.Quick estimate. Take planet mass M, volume V, radius R, density d same as Earth:M = dV ~ dR^3. Surface gravity force F on mass m organism: F ~ mM/R^2 ~ mR ~ mM^1/3, so gravity acceleration g = F/m ~ R ~ M^1/3.Gliese 667C f for example has likely mass M = 3.1, R = 1.5 according to the HEC. Both gives g ~ 1.5 times Earth gravity. [Be aware, the seeming consistency happens because they have assumed the same density too. But we, and they, are interested in Earth similar planets.]The largest of these have g ~ 1.8 IIRC.I should add that bacteria cell walls can cope with 40 atmospheres osmotic pressure differentials, meaning the same g differential. But beyond that, we find cellular life forms, even complex such, down to ~ 10 km depths in the oceans, or ~ 1000 atmospheres absolute pressure. Similarly, mantis shrimps can generate 1000's of g of acceleration by spring loading exoskeletons. So they would be able to move in 1000's of g's.I don't think gravity is a problem on terrestrials.
Last edited by Torbjörn Larsson, OM on Thu Jun 27, 2013 12:47 pm
