RGMBill wrote:If we were to switch Mars and Venus in our solar system, it has been said, we'd likely have three habitable worlds. Bigger is better further out, not so good close.The closer a planet is to its parent star, the more that star's radiation blasts apart water, and the more massive the planet has to be to retain the water components.Venus needed a moon to scoop off all that extra atmosphere. Mars just doesn't have the mass to hold one; if Mars were closer to the Sun, it would more resemble Mercury than Earth.
